events.description: Sir Francis Drake with an English force captures and occupies the Spanish colonial port of Cartagena de Indias for two months, obtaining a ransom and booty.

events.description: The assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back with heavy losses.

events.description: Jesse Fell burns anthracite on an open grate as an experiment in heating homes with coal.

events.description: Massachusetts governor Elbridge Gerry is accused of "gerrymandering" for the first time.

events.description: Gaetano Donizetti's opera La fille du régiment receives its first performance in Paris, France.

events.description: Giuseppe Verdi's opera I Lombardi alla prima crociata receives its first performance in Milan, Italy.

events.description: Kassa Hailu is crowned Tewodros II, Emperor of Ethiopia.
events.html: • 1855 – Kassa Hailu is crowned Tewodros II, Emperor of Ethiopia.[16]

events.description: Bernadette Soubirous's first vision of the Blessed Virgin Mary occurs in Lourdes, France.
events.html: • 1858 – Bernadette Soubirous's first vision of the Blessed Virgin Mary occurs in Lourdes, France.[18]

events.html: • 1861 – American Civil War: The United States House of Representatives unanimously passes a resolution guaranteeing noninterference with slavery in any state.[19]

events.description: King Amadeo I of Spain abdicates, triggering the proclamation of the First Spanish Republic.

events.description: The Meiji Constitution of Japan is adopted.

events.description: Anton Bruckner's 9th Symphony receives its first performance in Vienna, Austria.

events.description: Pope Pius X publishes the encyclical Vehementer Nos.

events.description: The Kingdom of Italy and the Vatican sign the Lateran Treaty.

events.description: LAPD Red Squad raid on John Reed Club art show in the U.S. results in the destruction of a dozen political artworks.

events.html: • 1990 – Nelson Mandela is released from Victor Verster Prison outside Cape Town, South Africa after 27 years as a political prisoner.[43]

events.html: • 1990 – Buster Douglas, a 42:1 underdog, knocks out Mike Tyson in ten rounds at Tokyo to win boxing's world Heavyweight title.[44]
